            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>
                   [Fragment A]
                   To Fabius Hermogenes, Roman knight, scribe of the [curule] aediles, adlected decurion, flamen of the divine Hadrian
                   in which priesthood he alone and first sponsored [scenic games] at his own expense, and [aedile]. The most splendid order 
                   of decurions honoured him [with a public funeral] and decreed for him an equestrian statue in the forum by subscription 
                   at public expense, on account of his devotion and diligence, and in his place it was decided not to substitute anyone as 
                   aedile in consolation to his father Fabius, who on account of the honours having been given to his son, gave 50,000 sesterces 
                   to the republic, from the interest of which, every year, on the 13th day before the Kalends of August, his [son's] birthday, 
                   5 denarii are to be given to each decurion there, and to the decurial cerarius scribes 37 1/2 denarii, to the copyists 12 1/2 denarii,
                   and to the lictores 25 denarii.
                   
                   [Fragment B]
                   In the temple of Roma and Augustus, it pleased the order of the decurions, in the presence of his father Fabius, that on the 
                   birthday of his son Hermogenes, gifts of money be distributed to those present in the forum before his statues, a formal
                   stipulation having been made.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>
                    This inscription is one of two (see also <ref target="EmpWor000104.xml">EmpWor000104</ref>) which attests to the dedicatory formula of the 
                    <ref target="monument-search.xml#ostiaaedes">Aedes of Roma and Augustus</ref> at <ref target="ancient_place.xml#Ostia">Ostia</ref>. 
                    This temple is archaeologically attested at the southern end of Ostia's forum. This is the same C. Domitius Fabius Hermogenes as in 
                    <ref target="EmpWor000124.xml">EmpWor000124</ref>, and some of the more ambitious restorations from this monument are the result of comparison 
                    with the inscription on his tomb near the Porta Romana. While Hermogenes was elevated to equestrian status, his father – L. Fabius Eutychus – was potentially 
                    a freedman (see e.g. Hartmann 2020, 138), and his mother, Artoria, potentially came from a family of craftspeople (see other Artorii: CIL 14.617a, 618, 251). 
                    Both father and son take pride in their apparitorial careers, especially in Rome, and which enriched the father to the extent that he could afford to pay 50,000 
                    sesterces to the public treasury for benefactions to be paid out the interest for the sum. In terms of the development of emperor worship at Ostia, it is remarkable 
                    that Hermogenes was the first sponsor scenic games for Ostia during his priesthood of the divine Hadrian. Hermogenes' name likely points to his
                adoption or some other close connection with C. Domitius Dexter, who was consul suffectus and later consul ordinarius in 196 CE (Hartmann 2020, 139; D'Arms 1976, 400-401), 
                and who was potentially responsible for his elevation to equestrian status. Hermogenes' public career at Ostia as decurion, flamen of the divine Hadrian, and aedile, 
                seems to have been cut short by his premature death.
                </p> 
            </div>
